ce:section.ce:para:
N2 physical adsorption and desorption was to analyze the physical structure of catalysts, and results show that compared with 5Ni/SiO2 and 5Ni-SiO2, catalysts prepared based on CQDs exist mesoporous effect (Fig. 1
                        ), the detailed physical and chemical properties as well as the metal loading of catalysts are summarized in Table 1
                        . It can be seen from Fig. 1a that the lines that represent the isothermal curve and pore width distribution of 5Ni/SiO2 are nearly horizontal, which indicates that the 5Ni/SiO2 catalyst has little pore and a small area. The adsorbed quantity of all xNi-SiO2-CQDs and 5Ni-SiO2 catalysts rises slightly at the relative pressure (P/P0) of 0–0.1, indicating the presence of a few micropores in the material. Hysteresis loop appears when P/P0 is 0.6–0.8, means that there exist mesoporous. The adsorbed quantity saturation is reached at P/P0 is 0.9–1.0, indicating that there are almost no large pores in the materials [34,35]. All xNi-SiO2-CQDs curves present a typical type IV isotherm with a H2 hysteresis loop, which means that the catalysts possess ink-bottle pores. The hysteresis loop of 5Ni-SiO2 appears at a relative pressure (P/P0) of 0.7–0.9, higher than those of xNi-SiO2-CQDs (0.6–0.8), indicating that the pore of 5Ni-SiO2 is large than xNi-SiO2-CQDs. It can also be seen from the pore distribution of Fig. 1b that the pore size of xNi-SiO2-CQDs is around 10 nm, and that of 5Ni-SiO2 is about 15 nm, large than xNi-SiO2-CQDs, which may be attribute to the weak interaction between SiO2 formed by TEOS hydrolysis under acid condition without CQDs. Furthermore, the xNi-SiO2-CQDs catalyst has a large specific surface area and pore volume, above 559 m2g−1 and 0.84 cm3g−1, respectively, which is much larger than the 5Ni/SiO2 catalyst by impregnation method (11 m2g−1, 0.007 cm3g−1) from Table 1. Additionally, when the Ni content increases, the surface area and the pore volume of xNi-SiO2-CQDs decrease slightly, which is due to the change in mass density with different metal contents [36]. The results of BET indicate that the presence of CQDs results in a strong interaction between SiO2, and after CQDs are removed, mesoporous around 10 nm forms.

The heat-resistant performance and long-term stability of catalysts were also investigated. It is necessary to study the heat-resistant performance for a catalyst being practically applied in the industry because the CO methanation is strongly exothermic, and a sharp temperature increase could occur during reaction and thus deactivate the catalysts. The thermal stability of catalysts is judged through the comparison of the activity at 500 °C before and after thermal treatment with reactant gas for 2 h at 650 °C (Table 2
                        ). For 5Ni/SiO2, the CO conversion decreases by 88.4% from 50.8% to 5.9% after thermal treatment, indicating poor thermal stability. In our previous research, Ni/SBA-16, prepared by impregnation method, exhibited significant decrease in catalytic activity after catalyst was calcined in reactant gases atmosphere, the CO conversion decreased by 71.1% from 100% to 28.9% and CH4 selectivity decreased by 56.0% from 96.2% to 42.3% [51]. The results indicate that though the molecular sieve with large surface area serves as support for the catalyst prepared by impregnation method, the catalyst would deactivate due to the agglomeration of metal particles at a high temperature caused by the weak interaction between metal and support. Nevertheless, the CO conversion of 5Ni-SiO2-CQDs shows slight decrease by 9.7% from 97.7% to 88.2%, and CH4 selectivity shows no obvious decrease, indicating that the thermal stability of the Ni-SiO2-CQDs catalyst synthesized by in-situ hydrothermal method is much better than that of the catalyst prepared by impregnation method. Meanwhile, Fig. 8
                         presents the results of the change of CO conversion and CH4 selectivity at 500 °C with time stream. It is observed that there is a slight decrease in CO conversion and CH4 selectivity of 5Ni-SiO2-CQDs catalyst at the beginning 20 h, but then remain stable at approximately 93% and 90%, respectively. However, for 5Ni/SiO2, CO conversion and CH4 selectivity quickly decrease to 20% and 80% at the beginning 20 h, and then present a slow decline trend. The results indicate that catalyst prepared by in-situ hydrothermal method via CQDs assisted exhibits better lifetime stability.

There exists slight deactivation during the thermal stability and long-term stability test, and carbon deposition on metal surface and agglomeration of active metal are the key factors that lead to catalyst deactivation. To explore the carbon deposition and metal agglomeration in catalyst after thermal stability, we use XRD patterns to study crystalline agglomeration, TEM to observe the metal dispersion and CHNS element technique to measure the amount of carbon in catalyst after thermal stability test (Fig. 9
                        , Fig. 10
                        ). The 44.7° and 52.0° peaks belong to the plane of Ni (111) and (200) (according to JCPDS PDF# 04–0850) for the Ni/SiO2 catalyst after reaction. There is a weak Ni peak at 44.7° for 5Ni-SiO2-CQDs catalyst, which may due to the migration and crystallization of the metal particles during reaction. In the TEM images, it can be clearly seen that Ni particles in 5Ni/SiO2 have agglomerated to large particles (approximately 200 nm), while most of the metal particles in 5Ni-SiO2-CQDs catalyst remain below 5 nm from the TEM images of the catalyst after thermal stability, means there is no obvious agglomeration of Ni particles in 5Ni-SiO2-CQDs. The results indicate that catalyst with metal particles confined in the channel of the support could effectively prevent the metal agglomeration. The amount of carbon in the 5Ni/SiO2 and 5Ni-SiO2-CQDs catalysts after thermal stability is 6.5% and 0.43%, respectively. Therefore, the 5Ni/SiO2 possess more carbon deposition while there is little carbon deposition in 5Ni-SiO2-CQDs catalyst, indicating that the assistance of CQDs in preparation could decrease the metal particles to about 4 nm, thus the carbon formation is suppressed, which could solve the problem of carbon deposit on catalyst, thus resulting in better stability.
